22. EN₂ at-tu-nu {mul}MUL šar-hu-tu₄ ša₂ mu-ši#-ti#
#tr.en: Incantation: You, O Zappu (Pleiades), (are) the splendid ones of the night,

23. nam-ru-ti ša₂ DINGIR-MEŠ GAL-MEŠ {mul#}MUL#
#tr.en: The brilliant ones of the great gods, O Pleiades!

24. a#-na hul-lu-qu lem-nu-ti ib-nu-ku-nu-ši {d}a-num : ina ša₂-ma-me MU#-ku-nu {d}IMIN-BI {mul#}[MUL]
#tr.en: Anu created you to destroy the wicked. In the heavens your name (is) Sebettu (i.e., the Seven).

25. [...]-nu# ki-li-lu {na₄}MUŠ.GIR₃ ra-ki-su me-ser₂-ri#
#tr.en: [. . .] . . a headband of serpentine, the ones girded with a belt.
#note: Ambose 2013: 200, line 71=A₃25 suggests we restore [{na₄}ša₂-da-n]u, "haemetite," at the head of the line; Jiménez 2014: 108 prefers to restore [za-ʾ-n]u, "[the ones who are adorn]ed." In light of ra-ki-su in the second half of the line, we expect a participle at its head. The reading at the end of this line and the several up to the ruling by and large follows Jiménez's (2014: 108).

26. [...] SU TI ša₂ til-le-e mu-šam-qi₂-tu₄ bu-lim
#tr.en: [. . .] . . of the weapons, who strike down the beasts.
#note: Note that til-le-e EDIN-ni occurs in Erra I 88 (see Cagni 1969: 66), where it refers to armor, "weapons of campaign" (lit. "weapons of the steppe").

27. [mu-sa]-ah#-hu EDIN da-li-hu A.AB.BA-MEŠ#
#tr.en: [Who throw] the steppe [into con]fusion, who roil the sea,
#note: Ambose (2013: 200) and Jiménez (2014: 108) prefer to restore [mu-pa-aš₂-š]i-ḫu, "[who pacif]y the steppe," but I think the parallel participle in the second cola suggests a more violent verb, such as seḫû, at the head of the line. The scant traces of the sign before ḪU will support either reading. CT 41 33: 5 explains a form of saḫû with one from dalāḫu (cited in CAD S, 208), suggesting their semantic overlap.

28. [x x x] x#-x#-tu₄ ga#-ru#-tu₄# DUMU-MEŠ {d}a-nim
#tr.en: [. . .] . . . mighty sons of Anu.

29. [...]-x#-ku-nu-ši
#tr.en: [. . .] to you.

30. [... da₃]-li₂#-li₂#-ku-nu lud-lul#
#tr.en: [. . .] I may sing your [pr]aises!
#note: Jiménez 2014: 108 suggests we restore [... a-na da-ra-a-ti] in the break. The parallel cited in the next note might suggest instead [bu-ul-li-ṭa-an-ni-ma] (line 26). There is easily room for eight (or more) signs.

31. ki-[ma A-MEŠ ID₂] eš#-šu#-ti# iṭ#-ru#-du# la#-bi#-ru#-ti TU₆.EN₂#
#tr.en: Jus[t as] the fresh [water of the river] expelled the old. Closing Incantation Formula.
#note: This is the first line in BMS 48, now joined to K.9083. Jiménez (2014: 108), citing Mayer 1990: 471, lines 24-25 as a parallel, suggests the above restoration. However, if it is correct, it must be a stub since the phrase restored here ought to rely on an imperative that occurred previously (it occurs in line 24 of the cited parallel, ina šīrīya ṭurud, "remove from my body" . . .) to set up the analogy. Moreover, the cited parallel shows the line occuring before the final praise. In the present case the line occurs after the final praise (in line 30), which is highly unusual. Perhaps the required imperative stood in line 29 and the scribe transposed lines 30 and 31.

